ne di temi fra retori e giuristi -- tDatazione e paternità delle Declamazioni maggiori pseudo-quintilianee -- tLe Declamazioni maggiori: istruzioni agli storici -- tFrigidam praeteritorum memoriam… Quelques remarques sur la mémoire dans les Déclamations majeures -- tPersonaggi storici nella declamazione latina: qualche riflessione su Alessandro Magno -- tSigle -- tIndice dei luoghi antichi e medievali0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe world portrayed by ancient declamation is often thought to be timeless; but it was in fact deeply rooted in the historical texture of the Roman Empire. The central aim of the volume is to recover this historical dimension, with particular reference to the so-called Major Declamations, a collection wrongly attributed to Quintilian, and now generally thought to be the work of several authors of the second and third centuries AD. Accordingly, many of the twenty studies collected here seek to anchor the Maiores to their period, exploring their chronology and authorship; their relationship to rhetorical education, Greek declamation, and philosophy; their depiction of earlier history; and their reflection of contemporary socio-cultural trends. Other essays concern their connection with legal theory and practice, and the relationship between juridical and declamatory language, real and fictitious court cases. A final set of studies focuses on the period when the collection was assembled (fourth century AD), reconstructing the late-antique forebear of all the extant manuscripts, speculating on the criteria which may have governed the selection of the pieces. The medieval reception of the Maiores is also investigated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Italian.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aJurisdiktion. 4aQuintilianus, Marcus Fabius : Declamationes maiores. 4aRömisches Reich. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aRoman law.  aRoman social history.  a[Quintilian].  adeclamation.1 aBreij, Bé, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrescia, Graziana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuongiorno, Pierangelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorcella, Aldo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoria, Carla Masi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnrico, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHömke, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrapinger, Gernot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamberti, Francesca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLentano, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLongo, Giovanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLovato, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLovato, Andrea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMacchioro, Riccardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPasetti, Lucia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPecere, Oronzo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRavallese, Maurizio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRizzelli, Giunio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSantorelli, Biagio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStramaglia, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStramaglia, Antonio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTraina, Giusto, econtributor.4ctb4https://i